\begin_layout Subsection
A temporary increase in productivity level (
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Goods Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The increase is 
\series bold
temporary
\series default
 but assume we don't know it (believe it's a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one-time bonanza
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we consider the wealth level (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

) is unchanged.
 Having 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite horizon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, a one-time increase has 0 impact on the wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first thing that needs to be done when analyzing a change - is understanding
 which curve does 
\series bold
not
\series default
 move.
 In this case, the demand curve won't change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supply curve will be affected [higher productivity means higher production
 - (1) even if no one knows in advance, at the end of the day there'll be
 more produced, (2) hiring more people, labor demand durve will move to
 the right] and shift to the right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every level of interest of the economy, there will be produced more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the demand surve didn't move, their intersection is now at a
 different point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that the demand durve didn't move, 
\series bold
doesn't mean that the demand doesn't change!
\series default
 It only means that 
\series bold
the demand function is the same
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the new equilibrium, there is more production, which leads to more demand,
 and lowers the interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everyone feels a bit wealthier today (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one-time bonus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 According to the Euler equation, such bonus will be saved, and not consumed
 at the moment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we get to a crucial difference between Macroeconomics and Microeconomics.
 As a single person, such one-time bonus can be completely spent.
 Consider an example with a fidherman.
 As you can't actually physically save fish, you 
\series bold
loan
\series default
 them fish and get money (more precise - 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

IOU
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 / a bond / promise - as there's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no money
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) with interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That can work if there is a 
\series bold
single
\series default
 fisherman in such situation, but when 
\series bold
everyone
\series default
 has it - everything changes.
 
\series bold
One
\series default
 person can lend to the rest, but it is impossible for everyone to do it
 in such primitive economy.
 
\series bold
Saving
\series default
 means that there is always somebody at the other end of the transaction,
 who preferes to consume more today and return later.
 When 
\series bold
everyone
\series default
 tries to sell bonds and nobody wants them, it pushes the price downwards,
 thus the interest rate must fall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trade done here is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fish vs.
 future promise to pay
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the price must fall until no one actually wants to sell, i.e until
 fish is 
\series bold
exactly
\series default
 the same valuable as the bond:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(c_{t})=\frac{1+r}{1+\delta}u(c_{t+1})
\]

\end_inset

Thus we can actually calculate, how much the interest rate has to fall so
 that people are indifferent between saving and consuming now (the first
 term should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq1$
\end_inset

).
 In a closed economy, people can't save in an equilibrium, as there is no
 one to lend to, so the interest rate must fall in order for the market
 to clear
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labor Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We always solve the goods market first, as it always includes the labor
 market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand for labor increases, as the level of productivity has risen (for
 every level of wage, employers will want to hire more people).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the interest rate is lower, labor supply curves shifts up (there is
 less point in working, saving is a good alternative).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium, the new (per-hour) wages level will be higher.
 Just from this qualitative analysis it is impossible to say what will happen
 to the level of employment (depends on the exact shapes of the curves).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis here is a simplification, we omit the non-important details
 (i.e how exactly do people find out the new level of wages, etc).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A temporary increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 (wealth)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Goods Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the opposite of the first exercies - no change in productivity here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to notice that we're dealing here with the impact 
\series bold
today
\series default
, without dealing with the future.
 We only look at how the 
\series bold
expectation
\series default
 of a better future makes influence on today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once households feel wealthier, they will want to consume more starting
 today, shifting the demand curve up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supply curve will shift left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summarized, such shock will have 2 effects: consume more and work less.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interest rate will rise (everyone wants to consume).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is impossible to tell exactly what will happen to the production.
 It depends on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

race
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between people who want ot increase consumption, and people who want to
 work less (increase their leisure).
 The final result depends on what people prefer more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labor Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wealth is higher.
 We suppose labor demand is unchanged (which is true 
\series bold
only for today
\series default
 - tomorrow it will be more demanded).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of increased wealth, people want to work less.
 But because of increased interest rate, people will want to work less.
 The final result, again, depends on which preference is stronger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 4 variables here we can't know: Y, C, W, L.
 But it doesn't mean they don't have constraints.
 For example, if production is higher - the labor is higher (meaning interest
 rate effect is more dominant), and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Permanent increase in productivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wealth actually increases (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\uparrow$
\end_inset

), because the change is permanent - and the productivity itself increases
 as well (
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Basically it is a combination of both previous examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Goods Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand curve only depends on wealth.
 People are actually wealthier, which shifts its to the right (for every
 level of interest rate - people will want to consume more).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is much harder to tell what will happen to the supply curve.
 The increasing productivity will tend to push it to the right, but the
 increased wealth will tend to push it to the left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At first glance, it seems as if we cannot say what will happen to the suppply
 curve.
 That is not completely true as we can use insights from the Euler equation.
 We know that it tells us the given 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 consumption path - the interest rate is equal to the time-preference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the consumption path is 
\series bold
stable
\series default
 - we assume that the interest level is 
\series bold
equal
\series default
 to the time-preference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the new steady state we may have higher path, but the interest rate will
 be the same (
\begin_inset Formula $r=\delta$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim the because of a permanent change starting at the moment, the economy
 will move to a new equilibrium.
 As we assume interest rate to be the same in the new situation, the supply
 of goods will necessarily move to the right, which depicts higher levels
 of both production and consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some assumptions are made here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A change in productivity doesn't change time preference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The new state arrives immediately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regardless of how much time it will take to reach it, Euler equation still
 holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An economy doesn't necessarily get to a steady state, but it can also oscilate
 around it (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

business cycles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) with fluctuations.
 With less rigit assumptions it is obviously possible.
\end_layout

