\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 Total amount of cash money (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bills in circulation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 Price level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The more productive the economy is, the more money is needed for people.
 Interest rate make a counter-effect (alternative opportunity), thus its
 increase decreases money demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supply is determined exogeneously by the central bank.
 In an equilibrium state, the supply and demand for money are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Money in the Neoclassical Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens to the real variables if the CB increases 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, by some degree? - 
\series bold
Nothing
\series default
.
 The intuition behind that is that we are able to calculate all real value
 without using nominal money at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What 
\series bold
will
\series default
 change are price levels.
 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{M}{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 must remain the same, thus an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 must be followed by an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
In neoclassical economy, increasing money by the central bank will increase
 all nominal values, without giving any real value.

\series default
 Money is 
\series bold

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Real wages and prices won't change, the effect will only be on the nominal
 values.
 That assumes completely flexible prices (no price rigidity).
 Notice that we do not discuss money distribution here, which may alter
 these results.
\end_layout

